ewtheorem{proposition}{Proposition} 	itle{The Number of Parts in the (Distinct) Partitions with Parts from a Set} \author{A.~David Christopher \ Department of Mathematics, The American College, Madurai, Tamil Nadu, India \ 	exttt{davidchristopher@americancollege.edu.in} } \date{}  egin{document} \maketitle  egin{abstract} The number of parts in the partitions (resp.\ distinct partitions) of $n$ with parts from a set were considered. Its generating functions were obtained. Consequently, we derive several recurrence identities for the following functions: the number of prime divisors of $n$, $p$-adic valuation of $n$, the number of Carlitz-binary compositions of $n$ and the Hamming weight function. Finally, we obtain an asymptotic estimate for the number of parts in the partitions of $n$ with parts from a finite set of relatively prime integers. \end{abstract} \section{Motivation and Basic Definitions} One can find a list of papers \cite{charlotte,erdos,hsien,lee,loxton,william} in the literature concerning the distribution of a given type of parts in a given class of partitions. In this article, we define the \emph{number of parts function} in two major classes of partitions, namely, in the partitions with parts from a given set and in the distinct partitions with parts from a given set. We derive their generating functions. All the results of this paper are obtained as the consequence of these generating functions. In Section~2, we present several recurrence identities for the following list of functions: the number of Carlitz-binary compositions of $n$, the number of prime divisors of $n$, $p$-adic valuation of $n$ and the Hamming weight function. In Section 3, we obtain an asymptotic estimate for the number of parts in the partitions of $n$ with parts from a finite set of relatively prime positive integers. The main classes of partitions and compositions of this paper are given in the following definition.  egin{definition} 
ormalfont Let $n$ be a positive integer. By a partition (resp. composition) of $n$, we mean an unordered (resp. ordered) sequence of positive integers whose sum equals $n$. Each summand in the sum is called a part.  egin{enumerate} \item A partition of $n$ is said to be a \emph{distinct} partition of $n$ if each part of it is different from the other parts. \item A partition (resp. composition) of $n$ is said to be a \emph{binary} partition (resp. composition) of $n$ if each part of it is of the form $2^k$ with integer $k\geq 0$. \item A composition of $n$ is said to be a \emph{Carlitz} composition of $n$ if each part of it is different from its adjacent parts. \item A composition of $n$ is said to be a \emph{Carlitz-binary} composition of $n$ if it is both Carlitz and binary. \end{enumerate} \end{definition} We introduce the \emph{number of parts function} which will be used for deriving several interesting results.  egin{definition} 
ormalfont Let $n$ be a positive integer and let $A$ be a set of positive integers.  egin{enumerate} \item The function $N^p_A(n)$ is defined to be the number of parts in the partitions of $n$ with parts from the set $A$. \item The function $N^q_A(n)$ is defined to be the number of parts in the distinct partitions of $n$ with parts from the set $A$. \end{enumerate} \end{definition} The list of partition functions and divisor-sum functions involved in the recurrence identities of this paper are given in the following definition.  egin{definition} 
ormalfont Let $n$ be a positive integer and let $A$ be a set of positive integers.  egin{enumerate} \item The function $p_A(n)$ (resp. $q_A(n)$) is defined to be the number of partitions (resp. distinct partitions) of $n$ with parts from the set $A$. \item The function $p_A^e(n)$ (resp. $p_A^o(n)$) is defined to be the number of partitions of $n$ with even (resp. odd) number of parts from the set $A$. \item The function $q_A^e(n)$ (resp. $q_A^o(n)$) is defined to be the number of distinct partitions of $n$ with even (resp. odd) number of parts from the set $A$. \item The function $	au_A(n)$ is defined by \[	au_A(n)=\sum_{\substack{a\mid n\ a\in A}}1. \] \item The function $	au_A^s(n)$ is defined by \[	au_A^s(n)=\sum_{\substack{a\mid n\ a\in A}}(-1)^{ rac{n}{a}-1}. \] \item The function $\sigma_A(n)$ is defined by \[\sigma_A(n)=\sum_{\substack{a\mid n\ a\in A}}a. \] \item The function $\sigma_A^s(n)$ is defined by \[\sigma_A^s(n)=\sum_{\substack{a\mid n\ a\in A}}(-1)^{ rac{n}{a}-1}a. \] \item The Hamming weight function, denoted $h(n)$, is defined to be the number of ones in the binary representation of $n$. \item Let $p$ be a prime number and let $q$ be a rational number. The $p$-adic valuation of $q$, denoted $\vartheta_p(q)$, is defined by $\vartheta_p(q)=r$, where $q=p^r rac{a}{b}$ with $\gcd(a,b)=1$. \end{enumerate} \end{definition} Throughout this article, we assume $x$ to be a real variable with $|x|<1$. It is well-known and easy to prove that  egin{equation}\label{gf1} \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}p_A(n)x^n=\prod_{a\in A}(1-x^a)^{-1} \end{equation} with $p_A(0)=1$,  egin{equation}\label{gf2} \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}q_A(n)x^n=\prod_{a\in A}(1+x^a) \end{equation} with $q_A(0)=1$,  egin{equation}\label{gf3} \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\left(p_A^e(n)-p_A^o(n)ight)x^n=\prod_{a\in A}(1+x^a)^{-1} \end{equation} with $p_A^e(0)=1$ and $p_A^o(n)=0$ 
ewline and  egin{equation}\label{gf4} \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\left(q_A^e(n)-q_A^o(n)ight)x^n=\prod_{a\in A}(1-x^a) \end{equation} with $q_A^e(0)=1$ and $q_A^o(0)=0$. From the Lambert series expansion one can readily get the following two generating functions:  egin{equation}\label{gf5} \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}	au_A(n)x^n=\sum_{a\in A} rac{x^a}{1-x^a}, \end{equation}  egin{equation}\label{gf6} \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\sigma_A(n)x^n=\sum_{a\in A} rac{ax^a}{1-x^a}. \end{equation} Since $|x|<1$, we have \[ rac{x^a}{1+x^a}=x^a-x^{2a}+x^{3a}-\cdots . \] This gives \[\sum_{a\in A} rac{x^a}{1+x^a}=\sum_{a\in A}(x^a-x^{2a}+x^{3a}-\cdots). \] In the right side sum, every exponent of $x$ is of the form $n=ka$ for some $a\in A$. Thus, the coefficient of $x^n$ in this sum is \[ \sum_{k}(-1)^{k-1}=\sum_{\substack{a\in A\ a\mid n}}(-1)^{ rac{n}{a}-1}=	au_A^s(n). \] Consequently, we have  egin{equation}\label{gf7} \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}	au_A^s(n)=\sum_{a\in A} rac{x^a}{1+x^a}. \end{equation} Similar argument gives  egin{equation}\label{gf8} \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\sigma_A^s(n)=\sum_{a\in A} rac{ax^a}{1+x^a}. \end{equation} \section{ Generating Functions for $N_A^p(n)$ and $N_A^q(n)$, and Six ways to Convolution and Recurrence Identities} \subsection{ Derivation with a Direct Application} In this subsection, we derive generating functions for $N^p_A(n)$ and $N^q_A(n)$ by defining appropriate bijective maps.  egin{theorem}\label{iden-1} Let $n$ be a positive integer and let $A$ be a set of positive integers. We have  egin{description} \item{(a)}  egin{equation} \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}N^p_A(n)x^n=\left(\prod_{a\in A} rac{1}{1-x^a}ight)\left(\sum_{b\in A} rac{x^b}{1-x^b}ight), \end{equation} \item{(b)}  egin{equation} N^p_A(n)=\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}p_A(k)	au_A(n-k), \end{equation} \item{(c)}  egin{equation} \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}N^q_A(n)x^n=\left(\prod_{a\in A}(1+x^a)ight)\left(\sum_{b\in A} rac{x^b}{1+x^b}ight), \end{equation} \item{(d)}  egin{equation} N^q_A(n)=\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}q_A(k)	au_A^s(n-k). \end{equation} \end{description} \end{theorem}  egin{proof} Let $b\in A$. Let $P_A^n$ be the set of partitions of $n$ with parts from the set $A$. Let $N_b^p(n)$ be the number of times $b$ occurs in $P_A^n$. Consider the mapping \[(b_1,b_2,\cdots ,b_s)	o (b_1,b_2,\cdots ,b_s,b,b,\cdots ,(	ext{k times})\ b) \] with $b_i\in A\setminus\{b\}$ and $b_1+b_2+\cdots +b_s+kb=n$. We observe that this mapping establishes a one-to-one correspondence between $P_{A\setminus\{b\}}^{n-kb}$ and the set of partitions of $n$ with part $b$ occurring exactly $k$ times and parts from the set $A$. This gives \[N_b^p(n)=p_{A\setminus\{b\}}(n-b)+2p_{A\setminus\{b\}}(n-2b)+3p_{A\setminus\{b\}}(n-3b)+\cdots.\] Now, we have  egin{align*} \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}N_b^p(n)x^n&=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\left(\sum_{k\geq 1}kp_{A\setminus\{b\}}(n-kb)ight)x^n\ &=(x^b+2x^{2b}+\cdots)\left(\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}p_{A\setminus\{b\}}(n)x^night)\ &= rac{x^b}{(1-x^b)^2}\prod_{a\in A\setminus\{b\}} rac{1}{1-x^a}\ &= rac{x^b}{1-x^b}\prod_{a\in A} rac{1}{1-x^a}. \end{align*} Since $N_A^p(n)=\sum_{b\in A}N_b^p(n)$, we have  egin{align*} \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}N^p_A(n)x^n&=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\left(\sum_{b\in A}N_b^p(n)ight)x^n\ &=\sum_{b\in A}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} N_b^p(n)x^n\ &=\sum_{b\in A}\left( rac{x^b}{1-x^b}\prod_{a\in A} rac{1}{1-x^a}ight)\ &=\left(\prod_{a\in A} rac{1}{1-x^a}ight)\left(\sum_{b\in A} rac{x^b}{1-x^b}ight) \end{align*} as expected in (a). Substituting (ef{gf1}) and (ef{gf5}) in (a), and equating the coefficients of $x^n$ on both sides gives (b). Let $b\in A$. Let $Q_A^n$ be the set of all distinct partitions of $n$ with parts from the set $A$. Let $N_b^q(n)$ be the number of times $b$ occurs in $Q_A^n$. Consider the mapping \[(b_1,b_2,\cdots,b_s)	o (b_1,b_2,\cdots ,b_s,b) \] with $b_i\in A\setminus \{b\}$ and $b_1+b_2+\cdots +b_s+b=n$. This mapping establishes a one-to-one correspondence between $Q_{A\setminus\{b\}}^{n-b}$ and the set of distinct partitions of $n$ in $Q_{A}^n$ having $b$ as a part. This gives $N_b^q(n)=|Q_{A\setminus\{b\}}^{n-b}|=q_{A\setminus \{b\}}(n-b)$. Now, we have  egin{align*} \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}N_b^q(n)x^n&=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}q_{A\setminus\{b\}}(n-b)x^n \&=x^b\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}q_{A\setminus\{b\}}(n)x^n\ \ &=x^b\prod_{a\in A\setminus\{b\}}(1+x^a) \ &= rac{x^b}{1+x^b}\prod_{a\in A}(1+x^a). \end{align*} Since $N_A^q(n)=\sum_{b\in A}N_b^q(n)$, we have  egin{align*} \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}N^q_A(n)x^n&=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\left(\sum_{b\in A}N_b^q(n)ight)x^n\ &=\sum_{b\in A}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}N_b^q(n)x^n\ &=\sum_{b\in A}\left( rac{x^b}{1+x^b}\prod_{a\in A}(1+x^a)ight)\ &=\left(\prod_{a\in A}(1+x^a)ight)\left(\sum_{b\in A} rac{x^b}{1+x^b}ight), \end{align*} as expected in (c). Substituting (ef{gf2}) and (ef{gf7}) in (c), and equating the coefficients of $x^n$ on both sides gives (d). \end{proof} As special cases of (b) of Theorem ef{iden-1} we have the following three results. First, we have a convolution-sum expression for the number of parts in the (distinct) partitions of $n$.  egin{corollary}Let $N^p(n)$ (resp. $N^q(n)$) be the number of parts in the partitions (resp. distinct partitions) of $n$ and let $p(m)$ (resp. $q(m)$) be the number of partitions (resp. distinct partitions) of $m$. We have  egin{description} \item{(a)}  egin{equation} N^p(n)=\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}p(k)	au(n-k), \end{equation} where $	au(m)=	au_{\mathbb N}(m)$, \item{(b)}  egin{equation} N^q(n)=\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}q(k)	au^s(n-k), \end{equation} where $	au^s(m)=	au^s_{\mathbb N}(m)$. \end{description} \end{corollary} As the second consequence of (b) of Theorem ef{iden-1}, we have a recurrence identity for the number of prime divisors of $n$.  egin{corollary} Let $A=\{2,3,5,7,11,\cdots\}$ be the set of all prime numbers. Then we have  egin{equation} N^p_A(n)=\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}p_A(k)\Omega(n-k), \end{equation} where $\Omega(m)$ denotes the number of prime divisors of $m$. \end{corollary} As the third consequence of (b) of Theorem ef{iden-1}, we have a recurrence identity for the $p$-adic valuation of $n$ for prime $p$.  egin{corollary} Let $p$ be a prime number and let $A=\{1,p,p^2,p^3,\cdots \}$. We have  egin{equation} N^p_A(n)=\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}p_A(k)\left(\vartheta_p(n-k)+1ight). \end{equation} \end{corollary} As a consequence of (d) of Theorem ef{iden-1}, we have an elegant recurrence relation for the Hamming weight function.  egin{corollary}\label{ham-rec} For integer $n\geq 2$, we have  egin{equation} h(n)=h(n-1)+1-\vartheta_2(n). \end{equation} \end{corollary}  egin{proof} Set $A=\{1,2,2^2,2^3,\cdots \}$. Then by basis representation theorem, we have $q_A(n)=1$ for every $n\geq 1$. By the definition: $q_A(0)=1$. Also we have $	au_A^s(n)=1-\vartheta_2(n)$ and $N_A^q(n)=h(n)$. Substituting these values in (d) of Theorem ef{iden-1} gives  egin{align*} h(n)&=\sum_{k=1}^{n}(1-\vartheta_2(k))\ &=h(n-1)+1-\vartheta_2(n) \end{align*} as expected. \end{proof}  egin{note} Corollary ef{ham-rec} can be written as $h(n)=\vartheta_2\left( rac{2^{n}}{n!}ight)$. \end{note} \subsection{ Inversion} The following result is an inversion formula for (b) and (d) of Theorem ef{iden-1}.  egin{theorem}\label{iden-2} Let $n$ be a positive integer and let $A$ be a set of positive integers. We have  egin{description} \item{(a)}  egin{equation} \sum_{k=1}^{n}N^p_A(k)\left(q_A^e(n-k)-q_A^o(n-k)ight)=	au_A(n), \end{equation} \item{(b)}  egin{equation} \sum_{k=1}^nN^q_A(k)\left(p_A^e(n-k)-p_A^o(n-k)ight)=	au_A^s(n). \end{equation} \end{description} \end{theorem}  egin{proof} From (a) of Theorem ef{iden-1}, we have  egin{equation}\label{man-iden-1} \left(\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}N^p_A(n)x^night)\left(\prod_{a\in A}(1-x^a)ight)=\sum_{b\in A} rac{x^b}{1-x^b}. \end{equation} Substituting (ef{gf4}) and (ef{gf5}) in (ef{man-iden-1}), and equating the coefficients of $x^n$ on both sides gives (a). From (c) of Theorem ef{iden-1}, we have  egin{equation}\label{man-iden-2} \left(\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}N^q_A(n)x^night)\left(\prod_{a\in A} rac{1}{1+x^a}ight)=\sum_{b\in A} rac{x^b}{1+x^b}. \end{equation} Substituting (ef{gf3}) and (ef{gf7}) in (ef{man-iden-2}), and equating the coefficients of $x^n$ on both sides gives (b). \end{proof} A recurrence identity of the form $g(n)=\sum_{k=0}^{n}\omega(k)f(n-k)$ with \[\omega(m)= egin{cases}1 &	ext{ if }m=0;\ (-1)^k &	ext{ if }m= rac{3k^2\pm k}{2} \end{cases} \] is called an Euler-type recurrence identity. As a consequence of Theorem ef{iden-2} we have an Euler-type recurrence identity for the number of parts in the partitions of $n$.  egin{corollary} We have  egin{description} \item{(a)}  egin{equation}\label{NOP} \sum_{k=1}^{n}N^p(k)\omega(n-k)=	au(n), \end{equation} \item{(b)}  egin{equation} \sum_{k=1}^{n}(-1)^{n-k}N^q(k)o(n-k)=	au^s(n), \end{equation} where $o(m)$ denotes the number of distinct partitions of $m$ with odd parts, $	au^s(m)=	au_{\mathbb N}^s(m)$ and $	au(m)=	au_{\mathbb N}(m)$. \end{description} \end{corollary}  egin{proof} Set $A=\mathbb N$. Then by Euler's pentagonal number theorem \cite{euler-pnt} we have \[ q_A^e(n-k)-q_A^o(n-k)=\omega(n-k).\] Substituting this value in (a) of Theorem ef{iden-2}, and equating the coefficients of $x^n$ on both sides gives (a). From (ef{gf3}) we have \[\prod_{n=1}^{\infty} rac{1}{1+x^n}=\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}(p_{\mathbb N}^e(m)-p_{\mathbb N}^o(m))x^m. \] In view of Euler's partition theorem \cite{euler}, we have  egin{equation}\label{ept} \prod_{n=1}^{\infty} rac{1}{1+x^n}=\prod_{n=1}^{\infty}(1-x^{2n-1})=\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}(-1)^mo(m)x^m. \end{equation} Substituting these values in (b) of Theorem ef{iden-2}, and equating the coefficients of $x^n$ on both sides gives (b). \end{proof} As another application of Theorem ef{iden-2} we express the number of prime divisors of $n$ as the convolution sum of $N^p_A(k)$ and $q_A^e(k)-q_A^o(k)$ with $A$ being the set of prime numbers.  egin{corollary} Let $A=\{2,3,5,7,11,\cdots\}$ be the set of all prime numbers. We have  egin{equation} \sum_{k=1}^nN^p_A(k)(q_A^e(n-k)-q_A^o(n-k))=\Omega(n). \end{equation} \end{corollary} A result similar to the above one is achieved for the $p$-adic valuation of $n$.  egin{corollary}\label{cor-3-iden-2} Let $p$ be a prime number and let $A=\{1,p,p^2,p^3,\cdots \}$. We have  egin{equation} \sum_{k=1}^nN^p_A(k)(q_A^e(n-k)-q_A^o(n-k))=\vartheta_p(n)+1. \end{equation} \end{corollary} As a special case of Corollary ef{cor-3-iden-2} we have a relation between Hamming weight function, the number of parts in the binary partitions of $n$ and the $2$-adic valuation of $n$.  egin{corollary} Let $N^p_{bin}(m)$ be the number of parts in the binary partitions of $m$. Define $s(0)=1$ and $s(m)=(-1)^{h(m)}$ for $m\geq 1$. Then we have  egin{equation} \sum_{k=1}^{n}N^p_{bin}(k)s(n-k)=\vartheta_2(n)+1. \end{equation} \end{corollary} \subsection{ Product with $\prod_{n=1}^{\infty}(1-x^n)$ and $\prod_{n=1}^{\infty}(1+x^n)^{-1}$} Multiplying the terms $\prod_{n=1}^{\infty}(1-x^n)$ and $\prod_{n=1}^{\infty}(1+x^n)^{-1}$, respectively, with the generating functions (a) and (c) of Theorem ef{iden-1} gives recurrence identities (separately) for $N^p_A(m)$ and $N^q_A(m)$ when $A
eq\mathbb N$, of which one is Euler-type.  egin{theorem}\label{iden-3} We have  egin{description} \item{(a)}  egin{equation} \sum_{k=1}^{n}N^p_A(k)\omega(n-k)=\sum_{k=1}^{n}	au_A(k)\left(q_{\mathbb N-A}^e(n-k)-q_{\mathbb N-A}^o(n-k)ight), \end{equation} \item{(b)}  egin{equation} \sum_{k=1}^n(-1)^{n-k}N^q_A(k)o(n-k)=\sum_{k=1}^{n}	au_A^s(k)\left(p_{\mathbb N-A}^e(n-k)-p_{\mathbb N-A}^o(n-k)ight). \end{equation} \end{description} \end{theorem}  egin{proof} From (a) of Theorem ef{iden-1}, we have \[\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}N^p_A(n)x^n=\left(\prod_{a\in A} rac{1}{1-x^a}ight)\left(\sum_{b\in A} rac{x^b}{1-x^b}ight). \] Multiplying both sides with $\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}(1-x^m)$ gives \[\left(\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}N^p_A(n)x^night)\left(\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}(1-x^m)ight)=\left(\prod_{a\in\mathbb N\setminus A}(1-x^a)ight)\left(\sum_{b\in A} rac{x^b}{1-x^b}ight). \] Now in view of Euler's pentagonal number theorem \cite{euler-pnt}, (ef{gf4}) and (ef{gf5}), we get (a). From (c) of Theorem ef{iden-1}, we have \[\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}N^q_A(n)x^n=\left(\prod_{a\in A}(1+x^a)ight)\left(\sum_{b\in A} rac{x^b}{1+x^b}ight). \] Multiplying both sides by $\prod_{m=1}^{\infty} rac{1}{1+x^m}$ gives  egin{equation}\label{prod-lemma} \left(\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}N^q_A(n)x^night)\left(\prod_{m=1}^{\infty} rac{1}{1+x^m}ight)=\left(\prod_{a\in \mathbb N\setminus A} rac{1}{1+x^a}ight)\left(\sum_{b\in A} rac{x^b}{1+x^b}ight). \end{equation} Now substituting (ef{ept}), (ef{gf3}) and (ef{gf7}) in the equation above, and equating the coefficients of like powers of $x$ on both sides gives (b). \end{proof} \subsection{ Logarithmic Differentiation} Logarithmic differentiation of the generating function of $p(n)$ gives the following relation:  egin{equation}\label{sigma} np(n)=\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\sigma(k)p(n-k). \end{equation} We wield the same technique for $N^p_A(n)$ and $N^q_A(n)$ to get results of similar kind.  egin{theorem}\label{iden-4} We have  egin{description} \item{(a)}  egin{equation} nN^p_A(n)=\sum_{k=1}^{n-1}N^p_A(k)\sigma_A(n-k)+\sum_{t=1}^{n}t	au_A(t)p_A(n-t), \end{equation} \item{(b)}  egin{equation} nN^q_A(n)=\sum_{k=1}^{n-1}N^q_A(k)\sigma_A^s(n-k)+\sum_{t=1}^{n}t	au_A^s(t)q_A(n-t). \end{equation} \end{description} \end{theorem}  egin{proof} Define the following: \[N^p_A(x)=\left(\prod_{a\in A} rac{1}{1-x^a}ight)\left(\sum_{b\in A} rac{x^b}{1-x^b}ight); \] \[N^q_A(x)=\left(\prod_{a\in A}(1+x^a)ight)\left(\sum_{b\in A} rac{x^b}{1+x^b}ight); \] \[p_A(x)=\prod_{a\in A} rac{1}{(1-x^a)}; \] \[q_A(x)=\prod_{a\in A}(1+x^a); \] \[	au_A(x)=\sum_{b\in A} rac{x^b}{1-x^b}; \] \[	au_A^s(x)=\sum_{b\in A} rac{x^b}{1+x^b}. \] Now taking the logarithm of $N^p_A(x)$ and then differentiating gives \[  rac{N^{p^\prime}_A(x)}{N^p_A(x)}=\sum_{a\in A} rac{ax^{a-1}}{1-x^a}+ rac{	au_A^\prime(x)}{	au_A(x)}. \] Multiplying both sides by $x$ and rearranging gives  egin{align*} xN^{p^\prime}_A(x)&=N^p_A(x)\left(\sum_{a\in A} rac{ax^{a}}{1-x^a}+ rac{x	au_A^\prime(x)}{	au_A(x)}ight)\ &=N^p_A(x)\left(\sum_{a\in A} rac{ax^{a}}{1-x^a}+ rac{x	au_A^\prime(x)}{N^p_A(x)}p_A(x)ight)\ &=N^p_A(x)\left(\sum_{a\in A} rac{ax^{a}}{1-x^a}ight)+x	au_A ^\prime(x)p_A(x). \end{align*} Now equating the coefficients of $x^n$ on extreme terms of the above chain of equalities gives (a). Taking the logarithm of $N^q_A(x)$ and differentiating gives \[ rac{N^{q^\prime}_A(x)}{N^q_A(x)}=\sum_{a\in A} rac{ax^{a-1}}{1+x^a}+ rac{	au_A^{s^\prime}(x)}{	au_A^s(x)}. \] Multiplying both sides by $x$ gives  egin{align*} xN^{q^\prime}_A(x)&=N^q_A(x)\left(\sum_{a\in A} rac{ax^{a}}{1+x^a}+ rac{x	au_A^{s^\prime}(x)}{	au_A^s(x)}ight)\ &=N^q_A(x)\left(\sum_{a\in A} rac{ax^{a}}{1+x^a}+ rac{x	au_A^{s^\prime}(x)}{N^q_A(x)}q_A(x)ight)\ &=N^q_A(x)\left(\sum_{a\in A} rac{ax^{a}}{1+x^a}ight)+x	au_A^{s^\prime}(x)q_A(x). \end{align*} Now equating the coefficients of $x^n$ on extreme terms of the above chain of equalities gives (b). \end{proof}  egin{corollary} We have  egin{description} \item{(a)}  egin{equation} nN^p(n)=\sum_{k=1}^{n-1}N^p(k)\sigma(n-k)+\sum_{t=1}^{n}t	au(t)p(n-t), \end{equation} \item{(b)}  egin{equation} nN^q(n)=\sum_{k=1}^{n-1}N^q(k)\sigma^s(n-k)+\sum_{t=1}^{n}t	au^s(t)q(n-t), \end{equation} \item{(c)}  egin{equation} nN_{bin}^p(n)=\sum_{k=1}^{n-1}N_{bin}^p(k)\left(2^{\vartheta_2(n-k)+1}-1ight)+\sum_{t=1}^nt(\vartheta_2(t)+1)b(n-t). \end{equation} \end{description} \end{corollary} \subsection{ Recurrence Identities over $A$} In this section, we derive recurrence identities for $N_A^p(n)$ and $N_A^q(n)$ over the set $A$.  egin{theorem}\label{roverA} Let $n$ be a positive integer and let $A$ be a set of positive integers. For $s\in A$, we have  egin{equation} N_A^p(n)-N_A^p(n-s)=p_A(n-s)+N_{A\setminus\{s\}}^p(n) \end{equation} with $p_A(0)=1$. \end{theorem}  egin{proof} By Theorem ef{iden-1},  egin{equation} \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}N_A^p(n)x^n=\left(\prod_{a\in A} rac{1}{1-x^a}ight)\left(\sum_{b\in A} rac{x^b}{1-x^b}ight). \end{equation} This gives  egin{align*} \left(\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}N_A^p(n)x^night)(1-x^s)&=\left(\prod_{a\in A\setminus\{s\}} rac{1}{1-x^a}ight)\left(\sum_{b\in A} rac{x^b}{1-x^b}ight)\ &=\left(\prod_{a\in A\setminus\{s\}} rac{1}{1-x^a}ight)\left( rac{x^s}{1-x^s}+\sum_{b\in A\setminus\{s\}} rac{x^b}{1-x^b}ight)\ &=x^s\prod_{a\in A} rac{1}{1-x^a}+\left(\prod_{a\in A\setminus\{s\}} rac{1}{1-x^a}ight)\left(\sum_{b\in A\setminus\{s\}} rac{x^b}{1-x^b}ight). \end{align*} Now writing the products in the right side as infinite sums in accordance with (ef{gf1}) and (a) of Theorem ef{iden-1}, and equating the coefficients of $x^n$ on both sides gives the expected end. \end{proof}  egin{theorem} Let $n$ be a positive integer and let $A$ be a set of positive integers. Let $s\in A$. We have  egin{equation} N_A^q(n)-N_A^q(n-s)+N_A^q(n-2s)+\cdots =N_{{A\setminus\{s\}}}^q(n)+q_{{A\setminus\{s\}}}(n-s)-q_{{A\setminus\{s\}}}(n-2s)+\cdots \end{equation} \end{theorem}  egin{proof} By Theorem ef{iden-1},  egin{align*}  rac{1}{1+x^s}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}N^q_A(n)x^n=&\left(\prod_{a\in A\setminus\{s\}}(1+x^a)ight)\left(\sum_{b\in A\setminus\{s\}} rac{x^b}{1+x^b}ight)\&+ rac{x^s}{1+x^s}\left(\prod_{a\in A\setminus\{s\}}(1+x^a)ight). \end{align*} Now writing the products in the right side as infinite sums in accordance with (ef{gf2}) and (c) of Theorem ef{iden-1}, and equating the coefficients of $x^n$ on both sides gives the expected end. \end{proof} \subsection{ Interplay with Carlitz Compositions} In this subsection we find some connections between the number of Carlitz's compositions, 2-adic valuation and the number of parts in the distinct partitions in terms of finite discrete convolutions.  egin{theorem}\label{iden-5} Let $cl_A(m)$ be the number of Carlitz compositions of $m$. We have  egin{description} \item{(a)}  egin{equation} cl_A(n)=\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}cl_A(k)	au_A^s(n-k), \end{equation} \item{(b)}  egin{equation} \sum_{k=0}^{n}cl_A(k)q_A(n-k)-\sum_{t=0}^{n-1}cl_A(t)N^q_A(n-t)=q_A(n) \end{equation} with $cl_A(0)=1$. \end{description} \end{theorem}  egin{proof} Heubach and Mansour \cite{heubach} derived the following generating function for the number of Carlitz compositions of $n$ with parts from the set $A$:  egin{equation}\label{carl} \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}cl_A(n)x^n= rac{1}{1-\sum_{a\in A} rac{x^a}{1+x^a}}, \end{equation} which can be written as \[\left(\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}cl_A(n)x^night)\left(1-\sum_{a\in A} rac{x^a}{1+x^a}ight)=1. \] The coefficient of $x^n$ on the left side term is \[cl_A(n)-\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}cl_A(k)	au_A^s(n-k). \] Since the coefficient of $x^n$ on the right side is zero, we have (a). Multiplying both sides of (ef{carl}) by $ rac{1}{\prod_{a\in A}(1+x^a)}$ gives  egin{center} $\Big(\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}cl_A(n)x^n\Big)$ $\left( rac{1}{\prod_{a\in A}(1+x^a)}ight)= rac{1}{\prod_{a\in A}(1+x^a)-\left(\prod_{a\in A}(1+x^a)ight)\left(\sum_{a\in A} rac{x^a}{1+x^a}ight)}.$ \end{center} This can be arranged as \[\left(\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}cl_A(n)x^night)\left[\left(\prod_{a\in A}(1+x^a)ight)-\left(\prod_{a\in A}(1+x^a)ight)\left(\sum_{a\in A} rac{x^a}{1+x^a}ight)ight]=\prod_{a\in A}(1+x^a). \] Then in view of (c) of Theorem ef{iden-1} and (ef{gf2}) we can write \[\left(\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}cl_A(n)x^night)\left[\sum_{l=0}^{\infty}q_A(l)x^l-\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}N^q_A(m)x^might]=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}q_A(k)x^k. \] Now equating the coefficients of like powers of $x$ on both sides gives (b). \end{proof}  egin{corollary} let $cl_b(m)$ be the number of Carlitz-binary compositions of $m$. We have  egin{description} \item{(a)}  egin{equation} cl_b(n)=\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}cl_b(k)(1-\vartheta_2(n-k)), \end{equation} \item{(b)}  egin{equation} \sum_{k=0}^{n}cl_b(k)\left(1-h(n-k)ight)=1 \end{equation} with $h(0)=0$. \end{description} \end{corollary}  egin{proof} Let $A=\{1,2,2^2,\cdots\}$. Then in view of basis representation theorem we have $q_A(m)=1$ and $N_A^q(m)=h(m)$ for every positive integer $m$. Moreover, we have $	au^s_A(m)=1-\vartheta_2(m)$. The result is immediate while we substitute these values in Theorem ef{iden-5}. \end{proof} \section{ Asymptotic Estimate of $N_A^p(n)$ when $A$ is a Finite Set} Throughout this section we assume $A=\{a_1,a_2,\cdots ,a_k\}$, a finite set of positive integers with $\gcd(A)=1$. Based on this assumption we find an asymptotic estimate for $N_A^p(n)$. To that end, we take cue from an earlier paper of the author \cite{david1}, where the function $p_A(n)$ was considered. It was shown there that $p_A(a_1a_2\cdots a_kl+r)$ is a polynomial in $l$ of degree $k$ for each $r\in\{0,1,2,\cdots ,a_1a_2\cdots a_k-1\}$ with the identical leading coefficient $ rac{(a_1a_2\cdots a_k)^{k-2}}{(k-1)!}$. This fact was used in \cite{david1} to arrive at the estimate of Netto \cite{Netto}: \[p_A(n)\sim rac{n^{k-1}}{(a_1a_2\cdots a_k)(k-1)!}. \] A quasi-polynomial representation of $p_A(n)$ found in \cite{david1} is recalled in the following lemma.  egin{lemma}\label{lemma2} Let $l$ be a non-negative integer and let $A=\{a_1,a_2,\cdots ,a_k\}$ be a set of positive integers such that $\gcd(A)=1$. For each $r\in\{0,1,\cdots,a_1a_2\cdots a_k-1\}$, the term $p_A(a_1a_2\cdots a_kl+r)$ is a polynomial in $l$ of degree $k-1$ with the leading coefficient $ rac{(a_1a_2\cdots a_k)^{k-2}}{(k-1)!}$. \end{lemma} The main result of this section is given below.  egin{theorem} Let $A=\{a_1,a_2,\cdots ,a_k\}$ be a set of positive integers such that $\gcd(A)=1$. Then we have  egin{equation}\label{mest} N_A^p(n)\sim rac{1}{k!} rac{ rac{1}{a_1}+ rac{1}{a_2}+\cdots + rac{1}{a_k}}{a_1a_2\cdots a_k}n^k. \end{equation} \end{theorem}  egin{proof} The crux of this proof is to show that $N_A^p(a_1a_2\cdots a_kl+r)$ is a polynomial in $l$ of degree $k$ with the leading coefficient \[ rac{\sum_{i=1}^{k}\left(a_i^{k-2}\prod_{\substack{j
eq i\ 0\leq j\leq k}}a_j^{k-1}ight)}{k!}\] for each $r\in\{0,1,\cdots ,a_1a_2\cdots a_k-1\}$. Once this is established, then we will have \[\lim_{l	o\infty} rac{N^p_A(a_1a_2\cdots a_kl+r)}{(a_1a_2\cdots a_kl+r)^{k}}= rac{1}{k!} rac{ rac{1}{a_1}+ rac{1}{a_2}+\cdots + rac{1}{a_k}}{a_1a_2\cdots a_k} \] for each $r\in\{0,1,\cdots ,a_1a_2\cdots a_k-1\}$, which is equivalent to the asymptotic estimate (ef{mest}). We will establish this main claim using induction over $|A|=k$. Since the term $a_i^{k-2}$ is involved in the leading coefficient, we take $k=3$ as the initial case for induction. Nevertheless the cases $k=1,2$ are needed to realise the case $k=3$. When $|A|=1$ the only way out is $a_1=1$. In this case we have $N_A^p(n)=n$, and the targeted estimate follows. To proceed further, we need the following observation: \[ N_{\{a\}}^p(n)= egin{cases} rac{n}{a} &	ext{ if }a\mid n;\ 0&	ext{ otherwise. } \end{cases} \] Assume $|A|=2$. That is, $A=\{a_1,a_2\}$ with $\gcd(a_1,a_2)=1$. Fix $r\in\{1,2,\cdots ,a_1\}$. Applying Theorem ef{roverA} $a_1$ times, we get  egin{align*} N_A^p(a_1a_2l+r)-N_A^p(a_1a_2(l-1)+r)&=\sum_{m=1}^{a_1}p_A(a_1a_2l+r-ma_2)\ &\ \ \ +\sum_{t=0}^{a_1-1}N_{\{a_1\}}^p(a_1a_2l+r-ta_2). \end{align*} Since $\gcd(a_1,a_2)=1$, the congruence equation $a_2t\equiv r\pmod {a_1}$ has a unique solution modulo $a_1$, say $t^*$. This gives  egin{align*} \sum_{t=0}^{a_1-1}N_{\{a_1\}}^p(a_1a_2l+r-ta_2)&= rac{a_1a_2l+r-t^*a_2}{a_1}\ &=a_2l+ rac{r-t^*a_2}{a_1}\ &=a_2l+k_1 \end{align*} for each $r\in\{0,1,\cdots ,a_1-1\}$, where $k_1$ is an integer constant. Next, we analyze the sum $\sum_{m=1}^{a_1}p_A(a_1a_2l+r-ma_2)$. Let $m\in\{1,2,\cdots ,a_1\}$. 
ewline Case i. Assume $r-ma_2<0$. In this case, consider the term $p_A(a_1a_2l+r-ma_2)$, which can be written as $p_A(a_1a_2(l-1)+a_1a_2+r-ma_2)$. Here we note that $0\leq a_1a_2+r-ma_2\leq a_1a_2-1$. Now, in view of Lemma ef{lemma2}, we have  egin{align*} p_A(a_1a_2(l-1)+a_1a_2+r-ma_2)=(l-1)+c_m, \end{align*} where $c_m$ is an integer constant.
